===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm}} {{term|forke||digging fork|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang}} {{term|force||lang=ang}}, {{term|forca||forked instrument used to torture|lang=ang}}, from {{proto|gem-pro|furkōn||furkô|fork|lang=en}}, from {{etyl|la}} {{term|furca||pitchfork, forked stake", ''also'' "gallows, beam, stake, support post, yoke|lang=la}}, of uncertain origin. The {{etyl|enm|-}} word was later reinforced by {{etyl|ONF.|-}} {{term|forque||lang=fro}} (= Old French {{term|forche|lang=fro}} whence French {{term|fourche|lang=fr}}), also from the Latin. Cognate also with {{etyl|frr|-}} {{term|forck||fork|lang=frr}}, {{etyl|nl|-}} {{term|vork||fork|lang=nl}}, {{etyl|da|-}} {{term|fork||fork|lang=da}}, {{etyl|de|-}} {{term|Forke||pitchfork|lang=de}}. Displaced native {{term|gafol|lang=ang}}, {{term|geafel|ġeafel|lang=ang}}, {{term|geafle|ġeafle|fork|lang=ang}}, from {{etyl|ang|-}}.

In its primary sense of "fork", {{etyl|la|-}} {{term|furca|lang=la}} appears to be derived from {{proto|ine-pro|ǵʰerk(ʷ)-||ǵʰerg(ʷ)-|fork|lang=en}}, although the development of the -c- is difficult to explain. In other senses this derivation is unlikely. For these, perhaps it is connected to {{proto|gem-pro|furkaz||firkalaz|stake, stick, pole, post|lang=en}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{recons|perg-||pole, post|lang=ine-pro}}. If so, this would relate the word to {{etyl|ang|-}} {{term|forclas||bolt|lang=ang}} (plural), {{etyl|osx|-}} {{term|fercal||lock, bolt, bar|lang=osx}}, {{etyl|non|-}} {{term|forkr||pole, staff, stick|lang=non}}, {{etyl|no|-}} {{term|fork||stick, bat|lang=no}}, {{etyl|sv|-}} {{term|fork|fork|pole|lang=sv}}.

